22 Sec. 31. 30-A MRSA §4326, as amended by PL 2023, c. 646, Pt. A, §§35 to 38, is
23 further amended to read:
24 §4326. Growth management program elements
25 A growth management program must include at least a comprehensive plan, as
26 described in subsections 1 to 4‑A 4, and an implementation program as described in
27 subsection 5.
28 1. Inventory and, analysis and needs assessment. A comprehensive plan must
29 include an inventory and analysis section addressing state goals under this subchapter and
30 issues of regional or local significance that the municipality or multimunicipal region
31 considers important. The inventory must be based on information provided by the State,
32 regional councils and other relevant local sources. The analysis must include 10-year
33 projections of local and regional growth in population and residential, commercial and
34 industrial trends; the best available projection of trends in economic activity; the projected
35 need for public facilities and services; and the vulnerability of and potential impacts on
36 natural resources. The department shall adopt rules to establish a tiered framework for
37 inventory requirements based on municipal and regional conditions.
38 The inventory and analysis section A comprehensive plan must include, but is not limited
39 to: a needs assessment that identifies existing conditions or desired conditions within the
40 municipality or multimunicipal region that are necessary to support housing, economic
41 growth and development; protect public health, safety and welfare of the community; and
42 protect the environment and critical resources. The plan must describe the public input
43 received to determine those needs.
Page 4 - 132LR1666(01)
1 A. Economic and demographic data describing the municipality or multimunicipal
2 region and the region in which it is located;
3 B. Significant water resources such as lakes, aquifers, estuaries, rivers and coastal
4 areas and, when applicable, their vulnerability to degradation;
5 C. Significant or critical natural resources, such as wetlands, wildlife and fisheries
6 habitats, significant plant habitats, coastal islands, sand dunes, scenic areas, shorelands,
7 heritage coastal areas as defined under Title 5, section 3316, and unique natural areas;
8 D. Marine-related resources and facilities such as ports, harbors, commercial
9 moorings, commercial docking facilities and related parking, and shell fishing and
10 worming areas;
11 E. Commercial forestry and agricultural land;
12 F. Existing recreation, park and open space areas and significant points of public
13 access to shorelands within a municipality or multimunicipal region;
14 G. Existing transportation systems, including the capacity of existing and proposed
15 major thoroughfares, secondary routes, pedestrian ways and parking facilities;
16 H. Residential housing stock, including housing for low-income and moderate-income
17 households, an assessment of community needs and environmental effects of municipal
18 regulations, an examination of the effect of excessive parking requirements that limit
19 the reuse of upper floors of buildings in downtowns and on main streets and an
20 identification of opportunities for accessory dwelling units;
21 H-1. Housing that meets the needs of older residents, including housing that is
22 rehabilitated, adapted or newly constructed to help older adults age in place;
23 I. Historical and archeological resources including, at the discretion of the municipality
24 or multimunicipal region, stone walls, stone impoundments and timber bridges of
25 historical significance;
26 J. Land use information describing current and projected development patterns;
27 K. An assessment of capital facilities and public services necessary to support growth
28 and development and to protect the environment and health, safety and welfare of the
29 public and the costs of those facilities and services; and
30 L. For a municipality or multimunicipal region that has adopted a local climate action
31 plan, a climate vulnerability assessment specific to the municipality or multimunicipal
32 region prepared by the municipality or multimunicipal region.
33 2. Policy Local goals and policy development. A comprehensive plan must include
34 a local goals and policy development section that relates the findings contained in the
35 inventory and analysis section to the state goals. The policies must:
36 A. Promote the state goals under this subchapter;
37 B. Address any conflicts between state goals under this subchapter;
38 C. Address any conflicts between regional and local issues; and
39 D. Address the State's coastal management policies under Title 38, section 1801 if any
40 part of the municipality or multimunicipal region is a coastal area.; and
Page 5 - 132LR1666(01)
1 E. Promote consistency with the State's climate action plan under Title 38, section 577.
2 3. Implementation strategy. A comprehensive plan must include an implementation
3 strategy section that contains a timetable for the implementation program, including land
4 use ordinances, ensuring that the goals established under this subchapter are met. These
5 implementation strategies must be consistent with state law and guidelines for the
6 implementation program as described in subsection 5 and must actively promote policies
7 developed during the planning process. The timetable must identify significant ordinances
8 to be included in the implementation program. The strategies and timetable must guide the
9 subsequent adoption of policies, programs and land use ordinances and periodic review of
10 the comprehensive plan, including a capital investment plan for the replacement and
11 expansion of public facilities and services required to meet projected growth and
12 development.
13 3-A. Guidelines for policy development and implementation strategies. In
14 developing its strategies and subsequent policies, programs and land use ordinances, each
15 municipality or multimunicipal region shall employ the following guidelines consistent
16 with the goals of this subchapter:
17 A. Except as otherwise provided in this paragraph, identify and designate geographic
18 areas in the municipality or multimunicipal region as growth areas and rural areas, as
19 defined in this chapter.
20 (1) Within growth areas, each municipality or multimunicipal region shall:
21 (a) Establish development standards;
22 (b) Establish timely permitting procedures;
23 (c) Ensure that needed public services are available; and
24 (d) Prevent inappropriate development in natural hazard areas, including flood
25 plains and areas of high erosion.
26 (2) Within rural areas, each municipality or multimunicipal region shall adopt land
27 use policies and ordinances to discourage incompatible development. These
28 policies and ordinances may include, without limitation, density limits, cluster or
29 special zoning, acquisition of land or development rights, transfer of development
30 rights pursuant to section 4328 and performance standards. The municipality or
31 multimunicipal region should also identify which rural areas qualify as critical
32 rural areas as defined in this chapter. Critical rural areas must receive priority
33 consideration for proactive strategies designed to enhance rural industries, manage
34 wildlife and fisheries habitat and preserve sensitive natural areas.
35 (3) A municipality or multimunicipal region may also designate as a transitional
36 area any portion of land area that does not meet the definition of either a growth
37 area or a rural area. Such an area may be appropriate for medium-density
38 development that does not require expansion of municipal facilities and does not
39 include significant rural resources.
40 (4) A municipality or multimunicipal region is not required to identify growth
41 areas within the municipality or multimunicipal region for residential, commercial
42 or industrial growth if it demonstrates, in accordance with rules adopted by the
43 department pursuant to this article, that:
Page 6 - 132LR1666(01)
1 (a) It is not possible to accommodate future residential, commercial or
2 industrial growth within the municipality or multimunicipal region because of
3 severe physical limitations, including, without limitation, the lack of adequate
4 water supply and sewage disposal services, very shallow soils or limitations
5 imposed by protected natural resources;
6 (b) The municipality or multimunicipal region has experienced minimal or no
7 residential, commercial or industrial development over the past decade and this
8 condition is expected to continue over the 10-year planning period;
9 (c) The municipality or multimunicipal region has identified as its growth
10 areas one or more growth areas identified in a comprehensive plan adopted or
11 to be adopted by one or more other municipalities or multimunicipal regions
12 in accordance with an interlocal agreement adopted in accordance with chapter
13 115 with one or more municipalities or multimunicipal regions; or
14 (d) The municipality or multimunicipal region has no village or densely
15 developed area.
16 (6) A municipality or multimunicipal region exercising the discretion afforded by
17 subparagraph (4) shall review the basis for its demonstration during the periodic
18 revisions undertaken pursuant to section 4347‑A;
19 B. Develop a capital investment plan for financing the replacement and expansion of
20 public facilities and services required to meet projected growth and development;
21 C. Protect, maintain and, when warranted, improve the water quality of each water
22 body pursuant to Title 38, chapter 3, subchapter I, article 4‑A and ensure that the water
23 quality will be protected from long-term and cumulative increases in phosphorus from
24 development in great pond watersheds;
25 D. Ensure that its land use policies and ordinances are consistent with applicable state
26 law regarding critical natural resources. A municipality or multimunicipal region, if
27 authorized to enact ordinances, may adopt ordinances more stringent than applicable
28 state law;
29 E. Ensure the preservation of access to coastal waters necessary for commercial
30 fishing, commercial mooring, docking and related parking facilities. Each coastal area
31 may identify and designate one or more critical waterfront areas and implement
32 policies to ensure protection of those areas or otherwise discourage new development
33 that is incompatible with uses related to the marine resources industry;
34 F. Ensure the protection of agricultural and forest resources. Each municipality or
35 multimunicipal region shall discourage new development that is incompatible with
36 uses related to the agricultural and forest industries;
37 G. Ensure that the municipality's or multimunicipal region's land use policies and
38 ordinances encourage the siting and construction of affordable housing within the
39 community and comply with the requirements of section 4358 pertaining to individual
40 mobile home and mobile home park siting and design requirements. The municipality
41 or multimunicipal region shall seek to achieve a level of at least 10% of new residential
42 development, based on a 5-year historical average of residential development in the
43 municipality or multimunicipal region, that meets the definition of affordable housing.
Page 7 - 132LR1666(01)
414 A municipality or multimunicipal region is encouraged to seek creative approaches to
425 assist in the development of affordable housing, including, but not limited to:
3 (1) Cluster housing;
4 (2) Reduced minimum lot and frontage sizes;
5 (3) Increased residential densities;
6 (4) Use of municipally owned land;
7 (5) Establishment of policies that:
8 (a) Assess community needs and environmental effects of municipal
9 regulations;
10 (b) Lessen the effect of excessive parking requirements for buildings in
11 downtowns and on main streets;
12 (c) Provide for alternative approaches for compliance relating to the reuse of
13 upper floors of buildings in downtowns and on main streets;
14 (d) Promote housing choice and economic diversity in housing; and
15 (e) Address disparities in access to educational and occupational opportunities
16 related to housing;
17 (6) Provisions for accessory dwelling units and greater density where such density
18 is consistent with other laws governing health and safety;
19 (7) Promotion of housing options for older adults that address issues of special
20 concern, including the adaptation, rehabilitation and construction of housing that
21 helps older adults age in place with adequate transportation and accessibility to
22 services necessary for them to do so in a safe and convenient manner; and
23 (8) Establishment of policies that affirmatively advance and implement the federal
24 Fair Housing Act, 42 United States Code, Chapter 45;
25 H. Ensure that the value of historical, archeological, tribal and cultural resources is
26 recognized and that protection is afforded to those resources that merit it;
27 I. Encourage the availability of and access to traditional outdoor recreation
28 opportunities, including, without limitation, hunting, boating, fishing and hiking, and
29 encourage the creation of greenbelts, public parks, trails and conservation easements.
30 Each municipality or multimunicipal region shall identify and encourage the protection
31 of undeveloped shoreland and other areas identified in the local planning process as
32 meriting that protection;
33 J. Develop management goals for great ponds pertaining to the type of shoreline
34 character, intensity of surface water use, protection of resources of state significance
35 and type of public access appropriate for the intensity of use of great ponds within the
36 municipality's or multimunicipal region's jurisdiction; and
37 N. Notwithstanding paragraph G, ensure that in a service center community at least
38 10% of the housing stock is affordable housing.
39 3-B. Future land use plan. A comprehensive plan must include a future land use plan
40 as described in this subsection.
Page 8 - 132LR1666(01)
1 A. Except as otherwise provided in this subsection, a future land use plan must identify
2 and designate geographic areas in the municipality or multimunicipal region as growth
3 areas and rural areas. This information may be presented in a narrative or map form.
4 B. A municipality or multimunicipal region may also designate any portion of land
5 area that is not a growth area or a rural area as a transitional area and as appropriate for
6 medium-density development that does not require expansion of municipal facilities
7 and does not include significant rural resources.
8 C. The department shall develop and maintain a catalog of implementation strategies
9 appropriate for various place types. Within the future land use plan, more place types
10 may be identified and designated to provide further guidance on the establishment or
11 modification of a municipality's or multimunicipal region's rate of growth ordinance,
12 zoning ordinance or impact fee ordinance.
13 D. A municipality or multimunicipal region is not required to identify growth areas
14 within the municipality or multimunicipal region for residential, commercial or
15 industrial growth if it demonstrates, in accordance with rules adopted by the
16 department pursuant to this article, that:
17 (1) It is not possible to accommodate future residential, commercial or industrial
18 growth within the municipality or multimunicipal region because of severe
19 physical limitations, including, without limitation, the lack of adequate water
20 supply and sewage disposal services, very shallow soils or limitations imposed by
21 protected natural resources;
22 (2) The municipality or multimunicipal region has experienced minimal or no
23 residential, commercial or industrial development over the past decade and this
24 condition is expected to continue over the 10-year planning period; and
25 (3) The municipality or multimunicipal region has no downtown or densely
26 developed area.
27 E. A municipality or multimunicipal region may identify as its growth areas one or
28 more growth areas identified in a comprehensive plan adopted or to be adopted by one
29 or more other municipalities or multimunicipal regions in accordance with an interlocal
30 agreement adopted in accordance with chapter 115 with one or more municipalities or
31 multimunicipal regions.
32 F. A municipality or multimunicipal region exercising the discretion afforded by
33 paragraph D shall review the basis for its demonstration during the periodic revisions
34 undertaken pursuant to section 4347‑A.
35 4. Regional coordination program. A comprehensive plan must include a regional
36 coordination program, which must be developed with other municipalities or
37 multimunicipal regions to manage shared resources and facilities, such as rivers, aquifers,
38 transportation facilities and others. This program must provide for consistency with the
39 comprehensive plans of other municipalities or multimunicipal regions for these resources
40 and facilities.
41 4-A. Addressing sea level rise. A municipality or multimunicipal region that is in the
42 coastal area may include in its comprehensive plan projections regarding changes in sea
43 level and potential effects of the rise in sea level on buildings, transportation infrastructure,
44 sewage treatment facilities and other relevant municipal, multimunicipal or privately held
Page 9 - 132LR1666(01)
415 infrastructure or property and may develop a coordinated plan for addressing the effects of
426 the rise in sea level. For the purposes of this subsection, "coastal area" has the same
437 meaning as in Title 38, section 1802, subsection 1.
4 4-B. Addressing climate risks and building resilience to natural hazards. A
5 municipality or multimunicipal region may include in its comprehensive plan projections
6 regarding risks posed by climate change as identified in its climate vulnerability assessment
7 prepared pursuant to subsection 1, paragraph L and the potential effects of those risks on
8 buildings, transportation infrastructure, sewage treatment facilities and other relevant
9 municipal, multimunicipal or privately held infrastructure, property or protected natural
10 resources and may develop a coordinated plan for addressing those risks and for building
11 resilience to natural hazards.
12 As used in this subsection, "protected natural resource" has the same meaning as in Title
13 38, section 480‑B, subsection 8.
14 5. Implementation program. An implementation program must be adopted that is
15 consistent with the strategies in subsection 3‑A the comprehensive plan prepared pursuant
16 to subsections 1 to 4 and this subsection. In developing its implementation program, a
17 municipality or multimunicipal region shall employ the following guidelines consistent
18 with the goals of this subchapter.
19 A. Within growth areas, a municipality or multimunicipal region shall:
20 (1) Establish development standards;
21 (2) Establish timely permitting procedures;
22 (3) Ensure that needed public services are available; and
23 (4) Prevent inappropriate development in natural hazard areas, including
24 floodplains and areas of high erosion.
25 B. Within rural areas, a municipality or multimunicipal region shall adopt land use
26 policies and ordinances to discourage incompatible development. These policies and
27 ordinances may include, without limitation, density limits, cluster or special zoning,
28 acquisition of land or development rights, transfer of development rights pursuant to
29 section 4328 and performance standards. The municipality or multimunicipal region
30 shall also identify which rural areas qualify as critical rural areas. Critical rural areas
31 must receive priority consideration for proactive strategies designed to enhance rural
32 industries, manage wildlife and fisheries habitats and preserve sensitive natural areas.
33 Sec. 32. 30-A MRSA §4346, 2nd ¶, as amended by PL 2021, c. 590, Pt. A, §10, is
34 further amended to read:
35 The department may enter into financial assistance grants only to the extent that funds
36 are available. In making grants, the department shall consider the need for planning in a
37 municipality or multimunicipal region, the proximity of the municipality or multimunicipal
38 region to other areas that are conducting or have completed the planning process and the
39 economic and geographic role of the municipality or multimunicipal region within a
40 regional context. The department shall give priority in making grants to any municipality
41 or multimunicipal region that has adopted a local climate action plan and, if the
42 municipality or multimunicipal region has adopted a comprehensive plan or growth
43 management program, prepared a climate vulnerability assessment pursuant to section
Page 10 - 132LR1666(01)
414 4326, subsection 1, paragraph L. The department may consider other criteria in making
425 grants, as long as the criteria support the goal of encouraging and facilitating the adoption
436 and implementation of local and multimunicipal growth management programs consistent
447 with the procedures, goals and guidelines established in this subchapter. In order to
458 maximize the availability of the technical and financial assistance program to all
469 municipalities, multimunicipal regions and regional councils, financial assistance programs
570 administered competitively under this article are exempt from rules adopted by the
581 Department of Administrative and Financial Services pursuant to Title 5, section 1825‑C
592 for use in the purchase of services and the awarding of grants and contracts. The
1503 department shall publish a program statement describing its grant program and advertising
1514 its availability to eligible applicants.
12 Sec. 33. 30-A MRSA §4346, sub-§5, as amended by PL 2013, c. 300, §6, is further
13 amended to read:
14 5. Coordination. State agencies with regulatory or other authority affecting the goals
15 established in this subchapter shall conduct their respective activities in a manner consistent
16 with the goals established under this subchapter, including, but not limited to, coordinating
17 with municipalities, regional councils and other state agencies in meeting the state goals;
18 providing available information to regions and municipalities and multimunicipal regions
19 as described in rules adopted pursuant to section 4326, subsection 1; cooperating with
20 efforts to integrate and provide access to geographic information and system data; making
21 state investments and awarding grant money as described in section 4349‑A; and
